  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/vad-hemolysis-acceptability",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "CFD-predicted hemolysis index is below the absolute clinical acceptance threshold for the Class III VAD across all 5 operating conditions",
      "description": "This claim asserts that the CFD model, employing the modified power-law hemolysis constitutive model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger coefficients re-fitted to Heuser-Opitz data), predicts a normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) below 0.005 g/100 L for all five flow-speed combinations specified in the COU. The claim is informed by an extensive body of supporting work: (1) the FDA-sponsored interlaboratory CFD study on the generic centrifugal pump (Stewart et al., 2012; Hariharan et al., 2011) in which 28 teams submitted velocity predictions compared against PIV measurements, establishing that well-resolved LES and high-fidelity RANS solutions achieve mean velocity errors below 10%; (2) the hemolysis sub-model validation reported by Taskin et al. (2012) across four pump geometries spanning the relevant shear-stress and exposure-time envelope; (3) Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification (5 000 samples, Latin hypercube) propagating inlet flow waveform variability, fluid viscosity uncertainty (±8%), and rotational speed tolerance (±15 RPM), yielding a 95th-percentile NIH of 0.0038 g/100 L, comfortably below the 0.005 g/100 L threshold; and (4) mesh-independence verification at three refinement levels (4.2 M, 11.7 M, and 31.4 M cells) demonstrating less than 2% change in volume-averaged shear stress between the two finest meshes. Collectively, these activities provide a coherent evidentiary narrative supporting the claim. Assessment team judgement: claim is considered credible at the achieved credibility levels documented in the associated credibility factors."
    }
  ],
